<section id="animations" class="section container">
  <h1>Animations</h1>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-6"><img src="12th pic.jpeg" class="img-fluid zoom"></div>
    <div class="col-md-6">
      <p>
        This new animation style often combine 3D modeling with comic or manga
        inspired visual techniques to create dynamic storytelling rooted in
        Black cultural experiences.

reinterpreted through a Black visual and cultural lens. The characters are rendered in stylized 3D with bold inked outlines, halftone textures, speed lines, and panel-like framing that evoke manga page composition while still moving fluidly in three-dimensional space. Instead of simply recoloring characters, the design language draws from authentic Black facial structures, hairstyles, body language, and fashion references, ensuring the characters feel culturally grounded. Lighting and shading emphasize deep contrast—often using rich blacks, graphic shadows, and expressive line work to echo manga ink techniques. Motion incorporates exaggerated manga-style action beats such as impact frames, smear drawings, and on-screen sound effects layered over 3D movement. The result is a Black manga-inspired animated comic aesthetic where the visual style, character performance, and cultural references are all intentionally rooted in Black identity rather than applied as surface-level representation. Some inspiration comes from animators such as: Trini animator Wendell McShine, Jamaican animator Corretta Singer, Jamaican character designer Daniel Brown, and 3D animation generalist Danielle Blaize. Essentially this animation would aim to be part of the Caribbean animation ecosystem in the anime caribe animation and new media festival in Trinidad and Tobago.  

